 getting bored with areas since nothing new ever happens in them. The progression of time is completely lacking in EQ. I have never seen a piece of history unfold on EQ, all of the history in EQ is just stories about what happend in the past. Most people would want to see the fall of the Iksar empire slowly happen. They want to see the huge battle of the erudites that caused the creation of the hole. They want to be a part of history and not be told it after the fact. Small GM events which change things in one day are not what I am talking about either, I mean things that would take months to unfold. The green mist in the Karanas was a neat thing, nothing ever came of it =/<br><br>People cannot alter the environment. Building things and the ability to have things destroyed in the environment is pretty key when a player wants to feel immersed in the world. The inability for a player to exact change on the world is a bad thing. This also is part of the static world problem.<br><br>The expansions have added new content but they trivialie the places before them. 99% of the loot in The old world is now useless. We all have boatloads of cash and there are very few real &quot;new&quot; players comming into the game anymore. The items like a Enameled black BP has become worthless, the dark reaver, Even most of the loot dropping from the boss mobs such as naggy or vox is outdated (except the haste). While new content is added we lose the content of the past as it becomes useless to us.<br><br>The classes in EQ are also a problem. People of the same class are too similar in EQ. Names are different but they look the same, wear the same armor, fight the same way, and have the same skills. We are all cookie cutter avatars, this is bad. A game that can manage a skill based character development which actually works (pushes for specialization along many lines) will far surpass Verants current system (supposedly SWG has a skill based system though so lets see how that is). There should be alot of variation in people, 2 warriors of the same age (exp) should have the ability to be very different in skills and abilities. Same with casters, very different approaches to spell casting.<br><br>Eventually a game will come out which takes all of the good points of EQ, AC, DAOC, UO, ect.... and will get rid of all the faults of each game. It will, if done right, be the game everyone wishes EQ was. Maybe Verant will be the creater of the game and call it EQ2, maybe another company will do it. One of these days though someone is gonna take the basic EQ game design, and improve on it and remove all of the restrictive problems it faces.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uomemydee.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ome Mydee</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/9/02 5:10:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2265.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: well</span><hr size=1> Dungeon Siege is an ok game.  If you are looking for a Diablo type of game that is.  Lots of hack n slash and light on the story and npc interaction.  If you are looking to play a BG2 or Torment type game dont bother with this one.<br><br>As for what Tropics mentions it sounds alot like Shadowbane.  <br><br>&quot;People cannot alter the environment. Building things and the ability to have things destroyed in the environment is pretty key when a player wants to feel immersed in the world. The inability for a player to exact change on the world is a bad thing. This also is part of the static world problem.&quot;<br><br>In Shadowbane you will be able to build kingdoms and destroy them through siege warfare.  Shadowbanes character development is also gonna be more interesting in that it allows for so many different combinations, also including types of magic and how one specializes.  Im pretty sure Shadowbane will be the most interesting character creation in a big game to date.<br><br><a href=http://members.cox.net/agathon1><img src=http://members.cox.net/agathon1/header1.jpg></a><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uwhizbangdustyboots.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Whizbang Dustyboots</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>O.G. (Original Gnome)</span><br>  Posts: 971<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/9/02 10:24:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2265.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.lby3.com/eq/whiz/flappy.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: well</span><hr size=1> I lost the past weekend to this, both on the single player game and the multiplayer world with my wife over the home network.<br><br>Basically, it's Diablo III, and it shamelessly follows every Diablo II convention except for the skill tree. Magic items have blue tags when they drop on the ground, you guzzle various sizes of red health potions and blue mana potions, items have magical prefixes and suffixes, and characters go up to silly levels (at least 120 in Dungeon Siege).<br><br>The single player game gets more challenging as it goes on, especially when you try to wrangle a large party through some of the nastier dungeons without one of them running off and aggroing a whole room full of stuff, not to mention keeping your poor old pack mule alive. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   But it's run on rails: While you can wander off to do 10 minute side trek minidungeons, it's inevitable that you'll find your way through the game, even if you don't pick up on all the quests -- many of which are worthless, or close to it.<br><br>The multiplayer world is much less linear -- there are numerous zones you'll never even see if you're doing the main quest -- but without NPCs to hire, it can be a little lonely. The main quest there -- reactivate all the teleport hubs -- also is right out of Diablo II, and there are THREE total sidequests, most of which you can do in under 10 minutes.<br><br>Despite this, it's a lot of fun. The character class system is neat (playing a wizard in single player and a warlock in multiplayer), and the game is jaw-droppingly beautiful. The many snow scenes can actually make you chilly.<br><br>Nice game, although it didn't ship with its editor or the second multiplayer world we were promised. Without either, I'm not sure this has the longterm appeal of either D2 or EQ. <p><a href="http://eq.guildmagic.com/character.cfm?ID=49189" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/whiz/whiz-photo-short.gif" height=60 width=468 alt="Whizbang Dustyboots" border=0></a><br><font size=1>Voted <a href="http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm40.showMessage?topicID=22.topic" target="_blank">second greatest wizard of all time</a> by Graffe.com!</font></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uwhizbangdustyboots.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Whizbang Dustyboots</A> at: 4/9/02 10:25:01 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ucerosofvazaelle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ceros of Vazaelle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 543<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/9/02 11:09:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2265.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: well</span><hr size=1> The designers of this game admit to taking elements from their favorite games and putting them into Dungeon Siege.<br><br>I've heard a lot of people compare it to Diablo and I never agree entirely.  The inventory and equipment system is straight out of Diablo and the spell system isn't that far off.  <br><br>The gameplay is very different, at least on the higher skill levels.  The RTS controls and multi-member party allow for a lot of strategy that you just *can't* have in Diablo. The combat itself feels like a mix between the RTS standard and Baulders Gate.<br><br>I have not played the game on easy, and from what I've seen of others playing it on easy, the strategy disappears and it becomes a hack and slash though..  This isn't a bad thing.  The combat is simply as involving as you want it to be.  I will say that if you are playing the game on easy, you are missing out however.<br><br>I really like the character advancement system.  Typically, I love Baulders Gate complexity in such areas of a game, but the approach they've taken in DS has a holistic feel.  Your characters have their abilities shaped by how you play them, not the other way around. It's gratifying to me to see my characters shaped by how I play.<br><br>The world is MUCH more immersive that Diablo as is the story line.  Diablo was never an RPG in my mind, it was an arcade game, and the feel of the world reflected this.  Every part of the game felt, of course, random and there was little cohesion.<br><br>This game borrows traits from Diablo and other games, but is as far Beyond Diablo as Half-Life was over Doom.  It is its own game. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uwhizbangdustyboots.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Whizbang Dustyboots</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>O.G. (Original Gnome)</span><br>  Posts: 972<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/9/02 11:53:30 am)</font>